The term "**entity**" encapsulates all things capable of moving around in a Minecraft world, that aren't blocks.

There are many kinds of entity classes in Minecraft:
- `Entity`, representing all entities.
- `LivingEntity`, living entities, which represent all entities that have health, can be damaged, killed and usually be affected by potion effects.
- `Player`, which are, well, players, including `ServerPlayer` that represent player entities on a server.
- And other non-living entities, like `ItemEntity`, `FallingBlockEntity`, and many others.

Only the most notable entity classes, that usually appear in KubeJS scripts will be documented here, since entities are quite complex and have tons of methods available on them.

# Overview

A **level** in Minecraft represents a physical dimension, in which blocks and [entities](/wiki/concepts/entity) may exist. Each dimension (Overworld, The Nether, The End and other modded and custom dimensions) is its own separate level. All levels are managed by the server on server-side.

As a Java class, {Level} defines behavior common to client and server-side levels.

# Instance methods



>>> #isClientSide
### `isClientSide`
<<<

>>> #isClientSide-description
**Syntax**
```js
level.isClientSide()
level.clientSide // read-only bean
```

Checks if the level is a client-side level.

**Return value**
`[js]true` if the level is client-side, `[js]false`, if it isn't (either a dedicated server or a logical server on a client).

In vanilla, this will be `[js]true` for {ClientLevel} and `[js]false` for {ServerLevel}.

<<<

